1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:In adversarial multiagent domains, security, commonly defined as the ability to deal with intentional threats from other agents, is a critical issue .
1-2:This paper focuses on domains where these threats come from unknown adversaries .
1-3:These domains can be modeled as Bayesian games; much work has been done on finding equilibria for such games .
1-4:However, it is often the case in multiagent security domains that one agent can commit to a mixed strategy which its adversaries observe before choosing their own strategies .
1-5:In this case, the agent can maximize reward by finding an optimal strategy, without requiring equilibrium .
1-6:Previous work has shown this problem of optimal strategy selection to be NP hard .
1-7:Therefore, we present a heuristic called ASAP, with three key advantages to address the problem .
1-8:First, ASAP searches for the highest reward strategy, rather than a Bayes Nash equilibrium, allowing it to find feasible strategies that exploit the natural first mover advantage of the game .
1-9:Second, it provides strategies which are simple to understand, represent, and implement .
1-10:Third, it operates directly on the compact, Bayesian game representation, without requiring conversion to normal form .
1-11:We provide an efficient Mixed Integer Linear Program implementation for ASAP, along with experimental results illustrating significant speedups and higher rewards over other approaches .
1-12:I.2.11 [Computing Methodologies]: Artificial Intelligence: .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:In many multiagent domains, agents must act in order to provide security against attacks by adversaries .
2-2:A common issue that agents face in such security domains is uncertainty about the adversaries they may be facing .
2-3:For example, a security robot may need to make a choice about which areas to patrol, and how often [16] .
2-4:However, it will not know in advance exactly where a robber will choose to strike .
2-5:A team of unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) [1] monitoring a region undergoing a humanitarian crisis may also need to choose a patrolling policy .
2-6:They must make this decision without knowing in advance whether terrorists or other adversaries may be waiting to disrupt the mission at a given location .
2-7:It may indeed be possible to model the motivations of types of adversaries the agent or agent team is likely to face in order to target these adversaries more closely .
2-8:However, in both cases, the security robot or UAV team will not know exactly which kinds of adversaries may be active on any given day .
2-9:A common approach for choosing a policy for agents in such scenarios is to model the scenarios as Bayesian games .
2-10:A Bayesian game is a game in which agents may belong to one or more types; the type of an agent determines its possible actions and payoffs .
2-11:The distribution of adversary types that an agent will face may be known or inferred from historical data .
2-12:Usually, these games are analyzed according to the solution concept of a Bayes Nash equilibrium, an extension of the Nash equilibrium for Bayesian games .
2-13:However, in many settings, a Nash or Bayes Nash equilibrium is not an appropriate solution concept, since it assumes that the agents" strategies are chosen simultaneously [5] .
2-14:In some settings, one player can (or must) commit to a strategy before the other players choose their strategies .
2-15:These scenarios are known as Stackelberg games [6] .
2-16:In a Stackelberg game, a leader commits to a strategy first, and then a follower (or group of followers) selfishly optimize their own rewards, considering the action chosen by the leader .
2-17:For example, the security agent (leader) must first commit to a strategy for patrolling various areas .
2-18:This strategy could be a mixed strategy in order to be unpredictable to the robbers (followers) .
2-19:The robbers, after observing the pattern of patrols over time, can then choose their strategy (which location to rob) .
2-20:Often, the leader in a Stackelberg game can attain a higher reward than if the strategies were chosen simultaneously .
2-21:To see the advantage of being the leader in a Stackelberg game, consider a simple game with the payoff table as shown in Table 1 .
2-22:The leader is the row player and the follower is the column player .
2-23:Here, the leader"s payoff is listed first .
2-24:1 2 3 1 5,5 0,0 3,10 2 0,0 2,2 5,0 Table 1: Payoff table for example normal form game .
2-25:The only Nash equilibrium for this game is when the leader plays 2 and the follower plays 2 which gives the leader a payoff of 2 .
2-26:311 978 81 904262 7 5 c 2007 IFAAMAS However, if the leader commits to a uniform mixed strategy of playing 1 and 2 with equal (0.5) probability, the follower"s best response is to play 3 to get an expected payoff of 5 (10 and 0 with equal probability) .
2-27:The leader"s payoff would then be 4 (3 and 5 with equal probability) .
2-28:In this case, the leader now has an incentive to deviate and choose a pure strategy of 2 (to get a payoff of 5) .
2-29:However, this would cause the follower to deviate to strategy 2 as well, resulting in the Nash equilibrium .
2-30:Thus, by committing to a strategy that is observed by the follower, and by avoiding the temptation to deviate, the leader manages to obtain a reward higher than that of the best Nash equilibrium .
2-31:The problem of choosing an optimal strategy for the leader to commit to in a Stackelberg game is analyzed in [5] and found to be NP hard in the case of a Bayesian game with multiple types of followers .
2-32:Thus, efficient heuristic techniques for choosing highreward strategies in these games is an important open issue .
2-33:Methods for finding optimal leader strategies for non Bayesian games [5] can be applied to this problem by converting the Bayesian game into a normal form game by the Harsanyi transformation [8] .
2-34:If, on the other hand, we wish to compute the highest reward Nash equilibrium, new methods using mixed integer linear programs (MILPs) [17] may be used, since the highest reward Bayes Nash equilibrium is equivalent to the corresponding Nash equilibrium in the transformed game .
2-35:However, by transforming the game, the compact structure of the Bayesian game is lost .
2-36:In addition, since the Nash equilibrium assumes a simultaneous choice of strategies, the advantages of being the leader are not considered .
2-37:This paper introduces an efficient heuristic method for approximating the optimal leader strategy for security domains, known as ASAP (Agent Security via Approximate Policies) .
2-38:This method has three key advantages .
2-39:First, it directly searches for an optimal strategy, rather than a Nash (or Bayes Nash) equilibrium, thus allowing it to find high reward non equilibrium strategies like the one in the above example .
2-40:Second, it generates policies with a support which can be expressed as a uniform distribution over a multiset of fixed size as proposed in [12] .
2-41:This allows for policies that are simple to understand and represent [12], as well as a tunable parameter (the size of the multiset) that controls the simplicity of the policy .
2-42:Third, the method allows for a Bayes Nash game to be expressed compactly without conversion to a normal form game, allowing for large speedups over existing Nash methods such as [17] and [11] .
2-43:The rest of the paper is organized as follows .
2-44:In Section 2 we fully describe the patrolling domain and its properties .
2-45:Section 3 introduces the Bayesian game, the Harsanyi transformation, and existing methods for finding an optimal leader"s strategy in a Stackelberg game .
2-46:Then, in Section 4 the ASAP algorithm is presented for normal form games, and in Section 5 we show how it can be adapted to the structure of Bayesian games with uncertain adversaries .
2-47:Experimental results showing higher reward and faster policy computation over existing Nash methods are shown in Section 6, and we conclude with a discussion of related work in Section 7. .
3 THE PATROLLING DOMAIN :
3-1:In most security patrolling domains, the security agents (like UAVs [1] or security robots [16]) cannot feasibly patrol all areas all the time .
3-2:Instead, they must choose a policy by which they patrol various routes at different times, taking into account factors such as the likelihood of crime in different areas, possible targets for crime, and the security agents" own resources (number of security agents, amount of available time, fuel, etc.) .
3-3:It is usually beneficial for this policy to be nondeterministic so that robbers cannot safely rob certain locations, knowing that they will be safe from the security agents [14] .
3-4:To demonstrate the utility of our algorithm, we use a simplified version of such a domain, expressed as a game .
3-5:The most basic version of our game consists of two players: the security agent (the leader) and the robber (the follower) in a world consisting of m houses, 1 .
