4-12:Recent work [17] has led to efficient mixed integer linear program techniques to find the best Nash equilibrium for a given agent .
4-13:However, these techniques do require a normal form game, and so to compare the policies given by ASAP against the optimal policy, as well as against the highest reward Nash equilibrium, we must apply these techniques to the Harsanyi transformed matrix .
4-14:The next two subsections elaborate on how this is done .
4-15:3.1 Harsanyi Transformation The first step in solving Bayesian games is to apply the Harsanyi transformation [8] that converts the Bayesian game into a normal form game .
4-16:Given that the Harsanyi transformation is a standard concept in game theory, we explain it briefly through a simple example in our patrolling domain without introducing the mathematical formulations .
4-17:Let us assume there are two robber types a and b in the Bayesian game .
4-18:Robber a will be active with probability α, and robber b will be active with probability 1 − α .
